<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1058,1563,1585]" box="[151,1058,1563,1585]" pageId="49" pageNumber="1008">
E t y m o l o g y: The trivial name, 
<emphasis box="[554,686,1564,1585]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="1008">atrigonatium</emphasis>
, is a compound Latin/Greek name
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1058,211,263]" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">
that stems from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[448,485,212,233]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">atri</emphasis>
(= black) and the Greek 
<emphasis box="[781,877,212,233]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">gonatium</emphasis>
(= knees); with reference to the black coloration on the distal region of the femora.
</paragraph>
